Let's leave it till tomorrow. Go to sleep! - And you?

541
00:56:40,660 --> 00:56:43,220
I'll look round for a bit.

542
00:56:43,300 --> 00:56:46,340
What about the salt-cellar? - You'll get it at 11 a.m.

543
00:56:46,460 --> 00:56:49,180
Why at eleven?

544
00:56:49,460 --> 00:56:53,420
I am leaving at twelve - I'm having lunch in Casablanca.

545
00:57:28,060 --> 00:57:31,610
Has anything happened here? - Nothing, I'm sorry to say!

546
00:57:43,660 --> 00:57:46,620
What now? Let's try it over there...

547
00:57:59,860 --> 00:58:03,650
Dammit... Not cleared up yet!

548
00:58:26,460 --> 00:58:29,420
Come here! Come!

549
00:58:31,060 --> 00:58:34,420
I feel a draught - it has to end here somewhere

550
00:58:41,860 --> 00:58:45,010
...because you lost the salt-cellar and W4C is still alive!

551
00:58:46,260 --> 00:58:49,410
If you don't make it right till twelve,

552
00:58:49,540 --> 00:58:52,820
you'll have to swallow the red ball!

553
00:58:54,860 --> 00:58:57,220
Listen well!

554
00:58:57,340 --> 00:59:00,410
Firstly: W4C!

555
00:59:00,540 --> 00:59:03,820
Secondly: Before

556
00:59:04,260 --> 00:59:07,620
Alice Roberts dives,

557
00:59:09,460 --> 00:59:13,010
the swimming pool has to be charged with 200.000 Volts.

558
00:59:14,460 --> 00:59:17,020
200.000 Volts.

559
00:59:17,620 --> 00:59:20,610
The body will be removed by a device made ready beforehand.

560
00:59:20,860 --> 00:59:23,820
That girl know too much!

561
00:59:24,140 --> 00:59:27,020
The cabin will be your command post.

562
00:59:27,460 --> 00:59:30,020
Now - don't forget! - Nn - o!

563
00:59:30,140 --> 00:59:33,020
You understood perfectly? - Yes.

564
00:59:33,460 --> 00:59:36,420
Yes or no? - I said I understood.

565
00:59:36,540 --> 00:59:40,010
I can only hear a whistling sound. It must be you mikes! ...Hear me?

566
00:59:40,140 --> 00:59:43,100
Just a moment!

567
00:59:46,460 --> 00:59:48,850
They were functioning all right...

568
00:59:48,980 --> 00:59:51,810
I can hear you now!

569
00:59:52,220 --> 00:59:56,010
Don't forget: Firstly and secondly!

570
01:00:00,860 --> 01:00:02,980
Out! Hmmm...

571
01:00:29,500 --> 01:00:32,460
What sort of a trap is this?

572
01:00:32,700 --> 01:00:35,660
We've been here before...

573
01:00:36,060 --> 01:00:38,420
Wait...

574
01:00:40,060 --> 01:00:43,420
And we didn't notice this here! Now, run!

575
01:00:45,380 --> 01:00:48,820
What's so precious about it? Don't sniff like that, there's a billion in that!

576
01:00:51,060 --> 01:00:54,810
Where is it though?! We'll have to ask.

577
01:01:05,660 --> 01:01:08,620
Up Pydie, up!

578
01:01:09,860 --> 01:01:13,410
Hallo, Chief, will you please - give me some information about salt?

579
01:01:14,860 --> 01:01:18,010
Foustka, the agent, speaking.

580
01:01:18,460 --> 01:01:22,010
What's all that nonsense?

581
01:01:22,860 --> 01:01:26,220
I told you I was a dietarian.

582
01:01:26,460 --> 01:01:29,210
I'm not allowed to use salt.

583
01:01:29,340 --> 01:01:32,410
That's why salt is double Dutch to me.

584
01:01:32,540 --> 01:01:36,010
Dutch? I have a dictionary...

585
01:01:36,540 --> 01:01:40,010
That fellow W4C told the young lady- it was worth a billion.

586
01:01:40,140 --> 01:01:42,650
Which young lady?

587
01:01:42,780 --> 01:01:45,820
The one they want to kill in the swimming pool tomorrow.

588
01:01:46,060 --> 01:01:49,610
You gave me her photo...

589
01:01:50,260 --> 01:01:52,620
You must prevent it!

590
01:01:52,740 --> 01:01:55,410
We can't have ladies killed in our swimming-pools!

591
01:01:55,540 --> 01:01:58,290
Think of our tourism!

592
01:01:58,460 --> 01:02:01,420
I hold you responsible for the pool!

593
01:02:01,660 --> 01:02:04,570
Got your regulation bathing-drawers? So what?!

594
01:02:04,660 --> 01:02:07,620
I say, Chief... Hallo...

595
01:02:12,260 --> 01:02:15,220
We shouldn't have taken the job, eh?

596
01:02:16,780 --> 01:02:19,740
Swimmers, get ready!

597
01:02:34,460 --> 01:02:37,420
When are you head-diving? - After the intermission. Why?

598
01:02:37,540 --> 01:02:40,420
I want to see it! - And the salt-cellar?

599
01:02:40,540 --> 01:02:43,500
At eleven, as I told you!

600
01:03:01,220 --> 01:03:03,210
Your ticket!

601
01:03:03,300 --> 01:03:05,770
Haven't got one. They're sold out.

602
01:03:05,860 --> 01:03:08,820
Then stay out!

603
01:03:11,460 --> 01:03:14,420
Pydie, try and make some confusion -

604
01:03:14,660 --> 01:03:17,620
so I can sneak in!

605
01:04:28,540 --> 01:04:32,420
Got it working? - Yes. 200.000 Volt.

606
01:04:38,060 --> 01:04:41,210
You sure nobody's in the pool yet?

607
01:04:42,060 --> 01:04:45,020
Well, you see

608
01:04:46,460 --> 01:04:49,420
To your stations!

609
01:04:53,700 --> 01:04:56,500
Everything O.K. Sir, as expected -

610
01:04:56,580 --> 01:04:59,410
the stadium is full of people - the trouble is,

611
01:04:59,540 --> 01:05:02,290
I can't get in.

612
01:05:02,380 --> 01:05:04,970
There were no tickets to be got...

613
01:05:05,060 --> 01:05:07,810
You bungler, you could have bought tickets

614
01:05:07,900 --> 01:05:10,620
in advance! - Kindly remember, Chief...

615
01:05:10,700 --> 01:05:13,980
Look up the directions - given in your booklet!

616
01:05:14,100 --> 01:05:17,810
I did - paragraph 15- how to work one's way into the Headquarters.

617
01:05:18,900 --> 01:05:21,620
Not a word about swimming-baths!

618
01:05:21,740 --> 01:05:24,620
Get in through the conduit,

619
01:05:24,700 --> 01:05:27,660
or disguised as the Mayor! Use your head, Foustka!

620
01:05:29,540 --> 01:05:33,010
Use your head... Says he...

621
01:05:34,140 --> 01:05:37,290
Disguised as the Mayor... I'd rather crawl in through the pipes!

622
01:05:48,060 --> 01:05:52,020
Monsieur... well you're finally here let's go inside... sofort...

623
01:05:59,460 --> 01:06:01,850
Your ticket! - Your ticket!

624
01:06:03,260 --> 01:06:05,410
No use talking! Your ticket! - Got no ticket? Stay outside!

625
01:06:07,140 --> 01:06:10,020
...the 100 metre breast stroke final

626
01:06:10,140 --> 01:06:14,020
for this year's championship.

627
01:06:16,380 --> 01:06:19,210
The lanes were drawn as follows

628
01:06:19,540 --> 01:06:23,500
Starting block No 1 - Ron Wyler of New Zealand,

629
01:06:26,860 --> 01:06:30,820
Block No 2 - Juan Alvarez, Ecuador...

630
01:06:32,860 --> 01:06:35,220
Isn't that your Edward?

631
01:06:35,340 --> 01:06:38,010
And he said he was a poor swimmer!

632
01:06:38,260 --> 01:06:41,170
In Ecuador children start swimming at the age of three.

633
01:06:41,300 --> 01:06:44,820
97,2% using the breast stroke and the back stroke, the rest.

634
01:06:45,260 --> 01:06:47,460
You know everything, Juan!

635
01:06:50,340 --> 01:06:53,220
About antique culture, for instance.

636
01:06:56,260 --> 01:06:59,220
But I'm taking an interest in it. Excuse me.

637
01:07:08,260 --> 01:07:12,090
Pydie! Bite... bite... bite!

638
01:07:18,060 --> 01:07:21,020
Bite it through and then sick him!

639
01:07:49,260 --> 01:07:52,220
Come in.

640
01:08:10,860 --> 01:08:13,820
To your blocks!

641
01:08:41,060 --> 01:08:44,420
...this inconspicuous Ecuadorian's stroke seems rather slow,

642
01:08:44,780 --> 01:08:48,010
but you ought to see his legs under the surface...

643
01:09:37,060 --> 01:09:40,210
The greatest surprise of this contest was the victory

644
01:09:40,340 --> 01:09:44,410
of the Ecuadorian - Juan Alvarez, whose style...

645
01:09:44,860 --> 01:09:47,250
Dear listeners, I can only say,

646
01:09:47,380 --> 01:09:50,210
it was a really wonderful show.

647
01:09:50,340 --> 01:09:53,300
We hope to get the champion to the microphone...

648
01:11:11,500 --> 01:11:14,460
The diving competition will begin

649
01:11:15,620 --> 01:11:19,580
with a double back-summersault executed by Miss Alice Roberts...

650
01:11:19,860 --> 01:11:21,980
Will you, please - at this happy occasion - say a few words

651
01:11:22,100 --> 01:11:25,090
to out listeners? We must prevent murder!

652
01:11:25,260 --> 01:11:28,220
Bravo! Bravo! Dear listeners, this admirable Ecuadorian athlete -

653
01:11:28,300 --> 01:11:31,420
the winner of the 100m race, in his finest sporting hour, not only

654
01:11:31,540 --> 01:11:35,420
speaks good Czech, but he's also made an appeal for World Peace!

655
01:12:48,380 --> 01:12:51,020
Hold this for me! - Right... Ladies and...

656
01:12:51,180 --> 01:12:53,820
You won't!

657
01:13:02,660 --> 01:13:05,090
What's bitten you, Edward?

658
01:13:05,340 --> 01:13:08,090
Come down! You mustn't dive! The pool is charged with high voltage!

659
01:13:08,260 --> 01:13:11,410
Take it easy, gentlemen! Let me prove it! Look!

660
01:13:15,060 --> 01:13:17,810
The salt-cellar!

661
01:13:22,140 --> 01:13:24,500
The salt-cellar!

662
01:14:25,300 --> 01:14:28,260
At eleven sharp!

663
01:14:34,260 --> 01:14:36,410
What's that?

664
01:14:40,060 --> 01:14:42,420
Jesus Christ...

665
01:14:45,660 --> 01:14:48,020
Dammit!

666
01:15:03,780 --> 01:15:06,900
A different sound.

667
01:15:07,180 --> 01:15:10,220
It's wet.

668
01:15:53,820 --> 01:15:56,810
Step on it!

669
01:15:58,140 --> 01:16:01,100
We must get him!

670
01:16:05,260 --> 01:16:08,970
We can't allow that sort of thing here! You are disqualified!

671
01:16:09,780 --> 01:16:12,740
Why? Good morning...

672
01:16:13,500 --> 01:16:16,460
Come here, Pydie!

673
01:16:16,820 --> 01:16:19,570
We shouldn't have taken this job!

674
01:16:19,700 --> 01:16:22,660
This is yours. Wait a minute!

675
01:16:41,100 --> 01:16:44,060
Faster! And to the left!

676
01:16:48,540 --> 01:16:51,500
Take off your shoes!

677
01:16:52,060 --> 01:16:55,020
They are indestructible.

678
01:16:55,220 --> 01:16:58,260
I sometimes think, I haven't chosen a nice profession.

679
01:16:58,340 --> 01:17:01,220
Oh, really?

680
01:17:16,620 --> 01:17:19,580
Bon voyage, my boy...

681
01:17:54,380 --> 01:17:57,340
Darling...

682
01:17:58,580 --> 01:18:01,540
We gotta overtake him!

683
01:18:09,660 --> 01:18:12,780
Three... Two... One... Go!

684
01:18:21,540 --> 01:18:24,420
Eight minutes left for us.

685
01:18:24,540 --> 01:18:27,500
Too short a time for lovers!

686
01:18:42,060 --> 01:18:45,020
He's got away again!

687
01:19:04,660 --> 01:19:07,620
You can choose!

688
01:19:09,500 --> 01:19:12,410
Marie Novakova, Hongkong,

689
01:19:12,660 --> 01:19:15,490
Marie Novakova, Hongkong, Marie Novakova, Hongkong...

690
01:19:21,460 --> 01:19:24,420
Your passports, please!

691
01:19:30,060 --> 01:19:33,020
The alarm clock! Fetch it!

692
01:19:39,140 --> 01:19:42,100
Good doggie...

693
01:19:51,940 --> 01:19:54,900
Hold this!

694
01:19:56,300 --> 01:19:59,610
Interesting. And old timepiece - keeping bad time...

695
01:20:10,340 --> 01:20:13,490
Hello, Edward. - Keeping bad time...

696
01:20:13,660 --> 01:20:16,780
The alarm-clock, I mean. - I know, Edward.

697
01:20:18,820 --> 01:20:21,780
No manners! - Thank you.

698
01:20:24,460 --> 01:20:27,130
A window-seat on the right, please!

699
01:20:27,260 --> 01:20:30,220
Not above the wing!

700
01:20:38,060 --> 01:20:41,020
Juan!

701
01:21:05,620 --> 01:21:08,580
Eat it!

702
01:21:16,660 --> 01:21:19,620
A pool full of corpses!

703
01:21:23,340 --> 01:21:26,620
W4C blown to kingdom come!

704
01:21:27,980 --> 01:21:30,620
Foustka,

705
01:21:30,860 --> 01:21:34,090
you've disrupted the whole European spy-network

706
01:21:34,260 --> 01:21:37,220
You've destroyed the reason

707
01:21:37,380 --> 01:21:40,210
for our existence!

708
01:21:40,460 --> 01:21:44,420
That's as may be - but the young lady was saved.

709
01:22:05,260 --> 01:22:07,410
And you bring me this stuff!

710
01:22:07,540 --> 01:22:10,500
It's said to be worth a milliard!

711
01:22:10,660 --> 01:22:13,620
A billion? - What am I to do with it?

712
01:22:13,820 --> 01:22:16,780
It's beyond my planned revenue.

713
01:22:16,900 --> 01:22:20,020
Which one is it? ...This one? - I'll soon know.

714
01:22:31,060 --> 01:22:34,020
Edward, the salt-cellars!

715
01:22:37,220 --> 01:22:39,610
Edu...

716
01:22:51,980 --> 01:22:55,020
I'll return the brief-case, Edward.

717
01:23:07,820 --> 01:23:10,810
There... the milliard is gone.

718
01:23:11,740 --> 01:23:14,810
Couldn't you offer resistance?

719
01:23:15,100 --> 01:23:18,220
This gimmick is out of order again!

720
01:23:18,660 --> 01:23:21,620
Why didn't your bitch jump at her and worry her?

721
01:23:21,740 --> 01:23:24,410
He was meant to jump on her and tear her to pieces! - He couldn't.

722
01:23:24,500 --> 01:23:27,460
What do you mean he couldn't? - Holding the salt-cellar in his mouth.

723
01:23:27,580 --> 01:23:30,730
Which salt-cellar? - The right one.

724
01:23:30,940 --> 01:23:34,010
Pydie, let him have it!

725
01:23:36,260 --> 01:23:40,010
Foustka!..

726
01:23:41,980 --> 01:23:44,810
Let me hug you!

727
01:23:46,020 --> 01:23:49,010
Now it's functioning!

728
01:23:53,740 --> 01:23:56,890
Mr. Foustka, why did that woman call you Edward?

729
01:23:57,060 --> 01:23:59,970
She was mistaking me for a schoolmate of hers.

730
01:24:01,700 --> 01:24:04,820
And... do you... know her intimately?

731
01:24:06,700 --> 01:24:08,660
Well...

732
01:24:17,780 --> 01:24:20,740
Mr. Foustka,

733
01:24:21,660 --> 01:24:24,220
this is most valuable indeed!

734
01:24:24,340 --> 01:24:27,620
It really is a plan for the military utilizations of Venus.

735
01:24:29,500 --> 01:24:32,620
You'll be promoted from Agent 13B

736
01:24:33,260 --> 01:24:36,650
to... Agent 13A!

737
01:24:38,020 --> 01:24:40,980
Pydie, here boy

738
01:24:41,180 --> 01:24:44,140
We shouldn't have taken this job.

739
01:24:44,860 --> 01:24:47,220
Why, Mr. Foustka?

740
01:24:47,340 --> 01:24:50,410
He said I'd be appointed Chief accountant - didn't he?

741
01:24:50,660 --> 01:24:53,620
And now an agent again, right?

742
01:24:59,180 --> 01:25:02,140
The end

